05343nam a22008535i 9781501715716DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20202021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017157167 a10.1515/97815017157162doi  a(DE-B1597)537406  a(OCoLC)1107057359  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBP195.A5bE93 2021 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a297.8609545522231 aEvans, Nicholas H. A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFar from the Caliph's Gaze :bBeing Ahmadi Muslim in the Holy City of Qadian /cNicholas H. A. Evans. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b7 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tNote on Names and Transliteration -- tIntroduction: A Troubled Relationship with Truth -- t1. The History of the Ahmadi-Caliph Relationship -- t2. An Enchanting Bureaucracy -- t3. A Failure to Doubt? Polemics and Sectarianism in Qadian -- t4. Prayer Duels to the Death: The Mubahala -- t5. Televising Islam: The Aesthetics of the Caliphate -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow do you prove that you're Muslim? This is not a question that most believers ever have to ask themselves, and yet for members of India's Ahmadiyya Community, it poses an existential challenge. The Ahmadis are the minority of a minority—people for whom simply being Muslim is a challenge. They must constantly ask the question: what evidence could ever be sufficient to prove that I belong to the faith?In Far from the Caliph's Gaze, Nicholas Evans explores how a need to respond to this question shapes the lives of Ahmadis in Qadian in northern Indian. Qadian was the birthplace of the Ahmadiyya Community's founder, and it remains a location of huge spiritual importance for members of the community around the world. Nonetheless, it has been physically separated from the Ahmadis' spiritual leader—the caliph—since partition, and the believers who nowadays live there and act as its guardians must daily confront the reality of this separation even while attempting to make their Muslimness verifiable.By exploring the centrality of this separation to the ethics of everyday life in Qadian, Far from the Caliph's Gaze presents a new model for the academic study of religious doubt: one that is not premised upon a concept of belief, but instead captures the richness with which people might experience problematic relationships to truth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAhmadiyya memberszIndiazQādiān. 0aAhmadiyya memberszIndiazQādiān. 0aAhmadiyyazIndiazQādiān. 0aAhmadiyyazIndiazQādiān. 0aEthnologyzIndiazQādiān. 0aEthnologyzIndiazQādiān. 0aFaith (Islam). 4aAnthropology. 4aIslamic Religion & Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Religion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAhmadiyya, Qadian, Caliphate, Islam, Religious Bureaucracy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW0 cprintz978150171570940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501715716?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501715716423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.co